<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Auto-Backup rules (v=3 unified-schema).

  What is being backed up:
    1. The strongbox v=3 slot files at
       files/strongbox/DP_QUANTUM_COIN_WALLET_APP_PREF.A.json /.B.json.
       These hold:
         * The scrypt salt (32 bytes; v=3 bumped from 16 on iOS so
           both platforms agree)
         * The scrypt+AES password-wrap of the random 32-byte
           mainKey (scrypt N=262144, r=8, p=1, 32-byte output)
         * The AES-256-GCM-sealed StrongboxPayload (wallets,
           customNetworks, secureItems, activeNetworkIndex,
           cloudBackupFolderUri, advancedSigning,
           cameraPermissionAskedOnce, currentWalletIndex), padded
           to a fixed 4 MiB bucket via ISO/IEC 7816-4 padding so
           wallet count cannot be inferred from on-disk file
           length. backupEnabled is intentionally NOT part of the
           encrypted payload — it lives in the SharedPreferences
           pref below as the canonical source of truth so the OS
           backup agent can read it pre-unlock.
         * An inner keyed checksum: HMAC-SHA-256 over the canonical
           sortedKeys JSON of the payload (sans the checksum
           field), keyed by HKDF-SHA-256(mainKey, salt=null,
           info="strongbox-payload-checksum-v3", L=32). The keyed
           checksum is byte-identical between iOS and Android for
           the same mainKey + payload.
         * The HMAC-SHA-256 file-level MAC keyed by HKDF(mainKey,
           salt, "integrity-v2")
    2. DP_QUANTUM_COIN_WALLET_APP_PREF.xml (SharedPreferences) for
       non-secret app state. The BACKUP_ENABLED pref is the
       CANONICAL store of the backup-enabled toggle (NOT a
       write-through mirror of a payload field). The Settings UI
       and onboarding write it directly; the strongbox payload
       does not carry a `backupEnabled` field at all, so there is
       no encrypted state to disagree with this pref.

  Cross-platform portability (notes for reviewers):
    The on-disk slot file is byte-for-byte identical to the iOS
    counterpart under the same inputs (password, salt, mainKey,
    AEAD nonces, wallet contents). A shared deterministic test-
    vector suite under tests/fixtures/strongbox-v3-vectors/ pins
    the format and is consumed by both platforms — see
    StrongboxPortabilityVectorTest. Bundled mainnet/testnet
    entries are NEVER written into the payload; they are
    re-prepended at runtime from R.raw.blockchain_networks so
    a future bundled-list update reaches every install without
    a migration.

  Why this is safe to back up:
    Every sensitive value in the strongbox file is sealed with
    AES-256-GCM under a 32-byte mainKey that is itself sealed
    with a scrypt-derived key (N=262144, r=8, p=1, 32-byte
    output). Without the user's wallet password the backup is
    useless to an attacker (including Google's backup storage,
    device images, or the receiving device during restore). The
    password is never stored on disk in a recoverable form.

  Runtime gate:
    WalletBackupAgent.onFullBackup() inspects BACKUP_ENABLED_KEY
    before calling super.onFullBackup(). The pref is the canonical
    setting, not a mirror of a payload field. The Settings UI and
    onboarding write it directly. The backup agent runs BEFORE
    unlock, so storing the toggle in a pre-unlock-readable surface
    (SharedPreferences) is required for the gate to work; the
    encrypted payload could never be consulted at this point. If
    the user has not explicitly opted in from the app Settings UI,
    the agent returns without emitting any data, so even with
    android:allowBackup="true" in the manifest nothing leaves the
    device.

  Restore behavior:
    On a new install on a new device, Android replays the backup
    into the same on-disk paths. Because the strongbox slot
    files travel together, the user only needs their original
    wallet password to unlock on the new device; no seed
    re-import is required. Cross-platform restore (Android slot
    file -> iOS, or vice versa) requires manually moving the
    slot file into the equivalent on-disk path; the v=3 portable
    schema guarantees that the foreign-platform reader can
    decrypt and validate it byte-for-byte (the test-vector suite
    enforces this).

  Exclusions:
    The AndroidKeystore-bound generation-counter pref file
    (qc_strongbox_counter_v1.xml) is explicitly excluded — its
    HMAC tag is signed by a non-extractable device-bound key
    that does not survive a device migration, so backing it up
    would mean the new device's keystore tag check rejects the
    counter on every unlock. The counter is re-initialised from
    the slot file's generation field on the new device.
-->
<full-backup-content>
    <include domain="file" path="strongbox/" />
    <include domain="sharedpref" path="DP_QUANTUM_COIN_WALLET_APP_PREF.xml" />
    <exclude domain="sharedpref" path="qc_strongbox_counter_v1.xml" />
</full-backup-content>
